1 - INTRODUCTION

  • This dataset is obtained from kaggle.com. And it is originally scrapped from dubizzle.com. Dubizzle is one of the famous online retail platforms in UAE (United Arab Emirates) to sell or buy any products (it is like US based Craigslist).

  • The dataset contains only auto ads from that website. The purpose of this project is to predict the price (continuous variable) of the vehicles using linear regression models and to find best model that fits the dataset.

  • The intention is to understand how car sale websites (e.g. KBB, Carvana) estimates the price of the cars within existing information.

Source (Kaggle) : https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/alihassankp/dubizzle-used-car-sale-data

Models : Linear Regression, Ridge, Lasso and ElasticNet

Model Evaluation : R-squared, RMSE , MSE

So our dataset consist of 9970 rows (observations) and 20 columns.

Here is the explanation of each columns:

title - Vehicle name with model details

price_in_aed - Vehicle price in united arab emirates dhirham

kilometer - How many kilometer the vehicle travelled

body_condition - Body condition of vehicle

mechanical_condition - Mechanical condition of vehicle

seller_type - Type of seller ( Dealer, Owner, Other)

body_type - Body type ( SUV, Sedan, Other)

no_of_cylinder - Number of cylinder

transmission_type - Vehicle transmission type ( Automatic Transmission, Manual Transmission )

regional_spec - Regional Specification of vehicle

horsepower - Horsepower

fuel_type - Fuel Type

steering_side - Steering side of the vehicle

year - Vehicle model year

color - Vehicle color

emirates - Emirates is like state

motor_trim - Motor trim type

company - Vehicle manufacture company name

model - Vehicle model

date_posted - Date of ad posted

3 - DATA PRE-PROCESSING

In [30]:
# There are 5 columns that has categorical values (e.g. fuel_type: electrical, diesel, gasoline)
# We would like to convert them to dummy variables (e.g. is_diesel: 1/0, is_electrical: 1/0)
# In each categorical value, we ommit one value to avoid having a linear dependency among columns.
# E.g. if there are 3 categories in a column, we convert it to 2 columns with binary values.

# Columns with categorical values, and dummy variable name to drop.
categorical_column_and_drop_dummy_pairs = [
    ('seller_type', 'Owner'),
    ('body_type', 'Other'),
    ('regional_specs', 'Other'),
    ('fuel_type', 'Electric'),
    ('company', 'other-make'),
]

for column, drop_val in categorical_column_and_drop_dummy_pairs:
    # Get individual columns for each dummy.
    dummies = pd.get_dummies(df[column])
    # Drop one dummy to avoid linear dependence
    dummies = dummies.drop(drop_val, axis = 1)
    # Drop the old columns with categorical values
    df = df.drop(column, axis=1)
    # Add dummy columns
    df = pd.concat([df, dummies], axis = 1)

# price column: remove comma from values and convert column to integer
df['price_in_aed'] = df['price_in_aed'].replace(',','', regex= True)
df['price_in_aed'] = df['price_in_aed'].astype(int)


# kilometer column:

df['kilometers'] = df['kilometers'].astype(int)
df = df[df['kilometers'] < 500000] # there were km values that were not possible. We filter them.


#body_condition column : rank the condition from 1 to 4

map_bodycondition = {
    'Perfect inside and out': 4,
    'No accidents, very few faults' : 3,
    'A bit of wear & tear, all repaired': 2,
    'Normal wear & tear, a few issues': 1
}

df['body_condition'] = df['body_condition'].replace(map_bodycondition)

# mechanical_condition column : rank the condition from 1 to 5

map_mechanicalcondition = {
    'Perfect inside and out': 5,
    'Minor faults, all fixed': 4,
    'Major faults, all fixed': 3,
    'Major faults fixed, small remain': 2,
    'Ongoing minor & major faults': 1
}

df['mechanical_condition'] = df['mechanical_condition'].replace(map_mechanicalcondition)

# no_of_cylinders column : replace 'unknown', 'na' and 'none' with 0. convert to integer
# Those are usually electrical vehicles.

df['no_of_cylinders'] = df['no_of_cylinders'].replace(['Unknown', '', 'None'], 0).fillna(0)
df['no_of_cylinders'] = df['no_of_cylinders'].astype(int)

# transmission_type column : convert to binary variable (manual = 0, automatic = 1)

df['transmission_type'] = np.where(df['transmission_type']=='Automatic Transmission',1,0)

# steering_side : convert to binary variable (left side = 1, right side = 0)

df['steering_side'] = np.where(df['steering_side']=='Left Hand Side',1,0)

# horse_power column

map_horsepower = {
    'Less than 150 HP' : 50,
    '150 - 200 HP' : 175,
    '200 - 300 HP' : 250,
    '300 - 400 HP' : 350,
    '400 - 500 HP' : 450,
    '500 - 600 HP' : 550,
    '600 - 700 HP' : 650,
    '700 - 800 HP' : 750,
    '800 - 900 HP' : 850,
    '900+ HP'      : 900,
    'Unknown'      : 0, # Zero values will be imputed below.
}

df['horsepower'] = df['horsepower'].replace(map_horsepower)


# date_posted column: Converting all dates to only year. (since some dates includes d/m/y information, some does not.) 
df['date_posted'] = pd.to_datetime(df['date_posted'], errors='coerce').dt.strftime('%Y')
df['date_posted'] = df['date_posted'].astype(int)


# year column:
# Data imputation: We predict missing year values using linear regression.
# Independent variables will be kilometers and date_posted columns, dependent varible will be year.
# We selected those columns as we expect kilometer to be large if the car is old.

df_subset_nonmissing = df.dropna(subset=['year', 'kilometers', 'date_posted'])
model = LinearRegression().fit(df_subset_nonmissing[['kilometers', 'date_posted']], df_subset_nonmissing['year'])
df['year'] = df.apply(lambda row: model.predict([[row['kilometers'], row['date_posted']]])[0] if pd.isna(row['year']) else row['year'], axis=1)
df['year'] = df['year'].astype(int)

# horsepower column: We'll use the average of the column to impute those missing NaN values.

horsepower_mean = df['horsepower'].mean()
df['horsepower'] = df['horsepower'].replace(0,horsepower_mean)

df_not_binary = df[['mechanical_condition','body_condition','no_of_cylinders','horsepower','kilometers','price_in_aed', 'year']]

    df[col_name] = boxcox(df[col_name])[0]
    df[col_name] = scale(df[col_name])

7 - CONCLUSION

When we run multiple regression models on dataset, we expect to find best model which gives lowest RMSE score and highest R-square result. As we know:

  • R-square shows us the percentage of variance in the outcome that is explained by the predictor variables. So, better R-square means better fit.

  • RMSE measures the average difference between values predicted by a model and the actual values. It provides an estimation of how well the model is able to predict the target value (accuracy),where the closer the score is to 0 the better performing the model is. So the RMSE value should be as low as possible.

In our regression results, if we rank highest R-square value and lowest RMSE, we get :

1) Linear 2) Ridge 3) Lasso

  • The evaluation values for Linear Regression show that it is a good fit for our dataset. But high R-square might show overfitting. To be sure, we also used Lasso and Ridge models.

  • We had large number of predictors in our models in this project. To prevent overfitting and reduce the impact of outliers, we also wanted to use Lasso and Ridge, since those models are useful when we have large number of predictors. And penalty term we added could reduce the impact of noises in our dataset. The results for these models also show that they did good job to fit the data.

  • However, We could not get good fit from ElasticNet model. The reason for this situation might be the ElasticNet models give better result when we have multicollinearity in dataset. But there was no multicollinearity among our predictors.
